	doi = {10.1080/13658816.2014.902950},
	abstract = {Introduction This is the Third Special Issue on Spatial Ecology in the International Journal of Geographical Information Science, with the first being published in 2011 (issue 3 of volume 25; Skidmore et al. 2011) and the second in 2012 (issue 11 of volume 26; Laffan et al. 2012). Spatial ecology addresses the effect of spatial patterning on ecological processes (Skidmore et al. 2011) and the papers in this special issue both address new topics and advance the themes of the preceding special issues. As is to be expected for a journal such as this, developing novel methods and applying established techniques in new ways are an important theme (e.g. Zhang et al. 2011, de Bie et al. 2012). In this issue, there are two papers that report the use of cost path analyses to better represent the connections between locations (Hanke et al. 2014, Hohl et al. 2014). Such approaches have the potential to make important refinements to many explicitly spatial analyses, and these papers contribute to an increasing literature on this topic (Laffan 2002, Adriaensen et al. 2003, Lyon et al. 2010, Greenberg et al. 2011, Etherington 2012, Nelson and Robertson 2012, Laffan and Taylor 2013, Radinger et al. 2013). {McCue} et al. (2014) also address a methodological issue, comparing the ability of two types of models to predict habitat use for a wide-ranging mammal. Consistent with applications across the fields of geography and ecology, the papers in this issue span a variety of spatial extent and grain, ranging from the micro-scale (Sillero and Gonçalves-Seco 2014) through landscape (Ficetola et al. 2014), regional (Beltrán et al. 2014, Bino et al. 2014, {McCue} et al. 2014) to continental scales (Peters et al. 2014). Species distribution modelling ({SDM}) is a recurring theme in spatial ecology and is represented here in several papers (Beltrán et al. 2014, Bino et al. 2014, Ficetola et al. 2014, Mateo Sánchez et al. 2014, {McCue} et al. 2014, Peters et al. 2014, Sillero and Gonçalves-Seco 2014). These papers address ways in which the representation of species distributions varies with scale (both grain and extent). Two papers introduce methods for mapping species ranges (Di Virgilio and Laffan 2014, Peters et al. 2014). Peters et al. delimit boundaries of the core range from discontinuous distributions predicted using {SDMs} – core range may be needed for studying source-sink dynamics. Conversely, Di Virgilio and Laffan presented methods for mapping variation in distributions within traditional range maps based on spatial analysis of point occurrence data to provide more fine-grained biodiversity information. Beltrán et al. (2014) use {SDM} to explore the ability of a regional conservation network to support multiple species of conservation concern under climate and land use change scenarios. This points to the need for considering appropriate spatial extents when managing for species persistence. Mateo Sánchez et al. (2014) demonstrate scale depen-dence in habitat selection for an endangered megavertebrate. As always, the accuracy and utility of {SDMs} are influenced by the choice and quality of data (Williams et al. 2012). Issues such as the selection of {GIS} data layers for {SDMs} (e.g. through consideration of collinear variables) as well as the spatial autocorrelation within a data layer are considered by many authors. The previous special issues contain several papers addressing data quality issues in spatial ecological modelling, including sample size, sampling bias, measurement error, spatial non-stationarity and model selec-tion (Leitão et al. 2011, Livne and Svoray 2011, Miller and Hanham 2011, Golicher et al. 2012, Moudrý and Šímová 2012). Here, Bino et al. (2014) focus on the effectiveness of multi-species survey techniques that are informed by {SDMs}, while two papers show the advantage of using {LiDAR} data to obtain better estimates of the habitat structure available to animals (Ficetola et al. 2014, Sillero and Gonçalves-Seco 2014). Papers in the previous special issues have primarily focused on terrestrial environ-ments (e.g. David Walter et al. 2011, Amboni and Laffan 2012, Burley et al. 2012, de Bie et al. 2012, Scull et al. 2012), with some marine (Hamylton 2012, Huang et al. 2012) and one aquatic (Chee and Elith 2012). This issue continues with the primary focus on terrestrial environments, but importantly there are two examples for aquatic environments (Hanke et al. 2014, Hohl et al. 2014). There is also a strong focus in this issue on vertebrate species, including mammals (Bino et al. 2014, Mateo Sánchez et al. 2014, {McCue} et al. 2014), reptiles (Di Virgilio and Laffan 2014, Sillero and Gonçalves-Seco 2014) and fish (Hanke et al. 2014). The inclusion of micro-organisms (Hohl et al. 2014) is further indication of the broad reach of spatial ecology. There remains considerable potential for the use of geospatial data and analysis tools to address important questions in spatial ecology (Skidmore et al. 2011, Laffan et al. 2012). This series of special issues serve to demonstrate the potential as well as the best practice of spatial ecology and will be followed by a fourth special issue on spatial ecology in {IJGIS} with the aim to further explore how the science and techniques of geographical information can continue to inform government and business in sustainable development and conservation of natural resources. References},
	pages = {1527--1530},
	number = {8},
	journaltitle = {International Journal of Geographical Information Science},
	author = {Laffan, Shawn William and Skidmore, Andrew K and Franklin, Janet},
	urldate = {2017-09-20},
	date = {2014},
	keywords = {{LiDAR}, spatial scale, habitat, cost path analysis, environmental modelling, landscape connectivity, species distribution mod-els, species range},
